      <description>&lt;p&gt;In Part 1, we completed the installation of Hugo (Extended version) on the Windows environment. Now, let&amp;rsquo;s officially create a blog and apply the &lt;strong&gt;Blowfish&lt;/strong&gt; theme.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&lt;h2 class=&#34;relative group&#34;&gt;1. Creating a New Hugo Project&#xD;&#xA;    &lt;div id=&#34;1-creating-a-new-hugo-project&#34; class=&#34;anchor&#34;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&#xD;&#xA;    &#xD;&#xA;    &lt;span&#xD;&#xA;        class=&#34;absolute top-0 w-6 transition-opacity opacity-0 -start-6 not-prose group-hover:opacity-100 select-none&#34;&gt;&#xD;&#xA;        &lt;a class=&#34;text-primary-300 dark:text-neutral-700 !no-underline&#34; href=&#34;#1-creating-a-new-hugo-project&#34; aria-label=&#34;Anchor&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;&#xD;&#xA;    &lt;/span&gt;&#xD;&#xA;    &#xD;&#xA;&lt;/h2&gt;&#xD;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Navigate to your desired folder (e.g., &lt;code&gt;C:\Project&lt;/code&gt;) and run the command below in your terminal to create a new site. I named the blog &lt;code&gt;my-blog&lt;/code&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
